WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.920
For those of you who don't know me, my name is Megan Harris.

00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:13.600
I am a data scientist at Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, and I'm here today because

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:17.400
I have a story to tell you all about data pipelines in R.

00:00:17.400 --> 00:00:21.160
But before I get into that, I do have a quick question for all of you.

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:26.520
You don't have to answer me out loud, but when you see this image, does it make you

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:30.600
feel anything or have any ideas on what it is?

00:00:30.600 --> 00:00:37.939
Well, this is my personal, 100% accurate representation of a data pipeline.

00:00:37.939 --> 00:00:43.000
And now you're all thinking I'm out of my mind, and I might be, but hear me out.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.520
Of course, this isn't an actual data pipeline, right?

00:00:46.520 --> 00:00:51.720
But rather the mental images and feelings I had when I was tasked with making a data

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:55.340
pipeline from scratch in my last position as a data specialist.

00:00:55.340 --> 00:01:00.180
The story I want to tell you all today is about how I created that pipeline in R within

00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:04.139
the context of me being a self-taught R programmer.

00:01:04.139 --> 00:01:09.099
Those of us that work in data, when we think of data pipelines, I sure as hell hope it

00:01:09.099 --> 00:01:10.940
does not look like that.

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:13.699
But hopefully it looks maybe something more like this.

00:01:13.699 --> 00:01:16.019
A perfect data pipeline.

00:01:16.019 --> 00:01:19.339
Clean processes, clean structures, great results.

00:01:19.339 --> 00:01:21.779
This is a pipeline to most of us.

00:01:21.779 --> 00:01:26.980
But in the last position I was in, the pipeline looked nothing like that at all.

00:01:26.980 --> 00:01:33.059
If we could even say there was a pipeline, it was very clunky, no structure, no automation,

00:01:33.059 --> 00:01:35.540
just bad vibes and recklessness.

00:01:35.540 --> 00:01:41.099
So although I have learned a lot and I have so much to share, I don't have a lot of time

00:01:41.099 --> 00:01:42.099
to talk.

00:01:42.099 --> 00:01:45.220
Y'all, we'll be lucky if we get under 19 minutes, I'm going to be honest.

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:51.260
So I pulled out four main points that I learned about creating pipelines during this journey.

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:55.500
These are going to touch on my first encounters within the data and the pipeline, the importance

00:01:55.500 --> 00:02:00.300
of identifying the environmental structures of the pipeline, embedding validations within

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:05.419
the pipeline, and understanding what sustainability looks like for the pipeline.

00:02:05.419 --> 00:02:09.419
Now keep in mind that all of these main points could easily be their own talks, their own

00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:11.059
lectures, their own courses.

00:02:11.059 --> 00:02:13.539
So I'll only touch on the biggest takeaways.

00:02:13.539 --> 00:02:19.800
However, I have created a list of example pipeline scripts, actual shell template documents

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:24.199
that you guys can all use that is in the repo for this talk on GitHub.

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:27.520
Yes, I know, great, right?

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:32.160
So with that out of the way, I think the best thing for me to do is go back to the beginning.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:35.080
During those first encounters I had with this pipeline.

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:39.320
And guys, I know I'm going to sound really out of my mind again, but the very first thing

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:45.440
I learned about making data pipelines in R was to not open R.

00:02:45.440 --> 00:02:49.440
Now I know you're thinking, Megan, we're at RStudioConf, what are you talking about?

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:52.880
I know, but hear me out, let me give you some context.

00:02:52.880 --> 00:02:58.059
This was me on my first day as a data specialist, my first professional data position, I'm self-taught,

00:02:58.059 --> 00:03:02.479
so I'm already coming in not familiar with things, but I'm also not familiar with the

00:03:02.479 --> 00:03:03.740
subject matter.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:06.500
This position was dealing with opioid data, right?

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:10.880
There was a lot of data existing everywhere, and the organization I was working directly

00:03:10.880 --> 00:03:16.360
with did not have any structure in place, nor did they have any expectations about what

00:03:16.360 --> 00:03:18.080
I was to do.

00:03:18.080 --> 00:03:23.399
So if I am a new self-taught programmer newbie, and I'm coming in with no direction, what

00:03:23.399 --> 00:03:25.119
did I do?

00:03:25.119 --> 00:03:29.720
So just like this dude is jumping headfirst to get to the Winchester, shout out to Shaun

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:36.279
of the Dead, I also dove in headfirst into RStudio as soon as I got any data, and that's

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:37.279
what I did.

00:03:37.279 --> 00:03:41.960
Whenever I got a new data set, I tried to create R programs immediately.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:45.080
And what I should have done was actually started investigating.

00:03:45.080 --> 00:03:50.399
I didn't ask basic questions, I didn't ask for code books, I didn't try to validate anything.

00:03:50.399 --> 00:03:53.759
It was just recklessness and vibes, I told you guys.

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:59.520
But I argue this point of not opening RStudio with an example of something that happened

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:01.440
to me that was traumatic.

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:03.520
I call it the Narcan story.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:07.919
Now for those of you who don't know, Narcan is a medication that is used to reverse opioid

00:04:07.919 --> 00:04:09.080
overdoses.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:12.279
So of course, working with this type of data, I'm going to see this information at some

00:04:12.279 --> 00:04:13.440
point.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:17.519
One day I get a data set and there's a variable in it called Narcan.

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:22.640
And like I did, opened up RStudio, quickly looked at it and saw, oh, Narcan has numbers

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:23.640
in it.

00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:24.640
Okay.

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:25.640
Numbers.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:30.320
So without doing anything else, I immediately started making automated reports, dashboards,

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:35.000
I'm feeling like I am a freaking superwoman, man, I'm awesome.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.359
And you know, I just I woke up in the middle of the night, like months after that, and

00:04:39.359 --> 00:04:43.440
I had just a random just eureka moment, kind of felt like something was wrong.

00:04:43.440 --> 00:04:47.359
I woke up and I was like, hmm, something ain't right, chief, what is it?

00:04:47.359 --> 00:04:53.119
So I went to RStudio IDE, opened it up, and I saw a value.

00:04:53.119 --> 00:04:55.079
And it was four plus.

00:04:55.079 --> 00:04:57.679
And guys, my heart sunk.

00:04:57.679 --> 00:05:00.600
Because four plus is not a number.

00:05:00.600 --> 00:05:02.359
Four plus is a string.

00:05:02.359 --> 00:05:07.440
So for months, I was calculating off of this variable that I did not even know how, but

00:05:07.440 --> 00:05:11.359
I was coercing a character variable into a numeric variable.

00:05:11.359 --> 00:05:15.239
So imagine the embarrassment of going back after everyone is relying on me for this and

00:05:15.239 --> 00:05:18.200
being like, hey, guys, it's wrong.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:23.679
So that was just one example of many times that happened to me.

00:05:23.679 --> 00:05:26.519
And clearly you can see here, I learned a lot.

00:05:26.519 --> 00:05:31.799
But the main thing I learned was to not jump into RStudio as soon as you get a dataset.

00:05:31.799 --> 00:05:36.760
If you do want to jump into it, only use it to give you a little bit of context, a little

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:40.160
bit of clues, so that you can ask more information.

00:05:40.160 --> 00:05:44.119
It was a really hard lesson that I had to learn to just go through this iterative process

00:05:44.119 --> 00:05:45.839
of asking questions.

00:05:45.839 --> 00:05:49.600
But doing so gave me just a little bit more clarity.

00:05:49.600 --> 00:05:53.200
So remember how that pipeline looked like in my head when I dove in head first with

00:05:53.200 --> 00:05:54.200
no information?

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:58.440
Well, now that I've had an investigation, it looks still messy.

00:05:58.440 --> 00:05:59.440
Okay.

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:00.440
It looks messy.

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:03.679
And it doesn't seem like much change, but I guarantee you, this is a different picture.

00:06:03.679 --> 00:06:04.679
Okay?

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:08.959
So I just enough started to clear up so that I could accept that fact that I needed to

00:06:08.959 --> 00:06:10.440
start building on this.

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:13.119
I needed to make some structure.

00:06:13.119 --> 00:06:17.040
So at this point, we're going to try to add some environmental structure, right?

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:21.440
So the biggest thing I learned about environmental structures is that data pipelines can actually

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:24.140
exist in two types of environments.

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:27.760
Something that I'm terming as external and internal environments.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:31.799
Now there's probably way more sophisticated ways to think about this and break this down,

00:06:31.799 --> 00:06:36.640
but I'm a beginner, and this is what my beginner brain made sense.

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:38.440
This is what made sense.

00:06:38.440 --> 00:06:43.399
So when starting out, I had realized I had external things outside of my computer that

00:06:43.399 --> 00:06:48.440
was affecting the data inside of my computer, but also things inside of my computer, inside

00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:51.600
of RStudio that was affecting it as well.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:53.359
And I'll explain both of them.

00:06:53.359 --> 00:06:58.160
So when I say external environment, I'm talking about more abstract concepts.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:07:04.160
I'm talking about any kind of data interactions, decisions, admin policies that can affect

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:08.480
the flow of the data, even the technology that's used for data collection, and even

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.519
the data literacy of whoever you are working with.

00:07:11.519 --> 00:07:17.160
It was so important to identify all of these concepts because at some point, they are going

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:19.880
to affect your internal flow of your pipeline.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:25.320
It's going to affect how you end up working with and structuring your data internally.

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:29.119
The internal environment is what most people think about when they hear the words data

00:07:29.119 --> 00:07:30.119
pipeline.

00:07:30.119 --> 00:07:34.040
They think about the actual file structures, the flow of things happening internally, the

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:37.760
logic of processing, and even the data security and storage methods.

00:07:37.760 --> 00:07:41.600
Now, it should go without saying that this isn't the reality, right?

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:46.200
We don't have two separate environments that exist in silos.

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:49.559
There's external things that affect internal things and vice versa.

00:07:49.559 --> 00:07:53.239
And this is a challenge that most every data person knows well, even if we don't think

00:07:53.239 --> 00:07:55.559
about environments in this way.

00:07:55.559 --> 00:08:01.920
I'm sure that if any of you work in nonprofit or academia or government or anywhere, you

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:06.760
probably have some form of bureaucracy affecting what you do.

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:09.279
Maybe even conflicting interests and decisions.

00:08:09.279 --> 00:08:10.920
That's an example of this.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:16.079
So what helped me to better navigate the interactions between these two environments was to repeatedly

00:08:16.079 --> 00:08:21.239
tackle each environment by introducing some structure, some documentation for one and

00:08:21.239 --> 00:08:23.160
adjusting for the other.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:26.760
So I just want to give a really quick example of just some documents that I made to try

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:28.480
to help me out with this.

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:32.760
So when I was thinking about structuring my external environment, you guys got to remember,

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:35.200
I was a one-person data team, really.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:36.200
I was.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:40.599
I was the only person coding in R. So everyone else that I was working with had no concept

00:08:40.599 --> 00:08:43.479
of this, did not do any coding, whatever.

00:08:43.479 --> 00:08:49.039
So my method of trying to introduce some structure was to get everybody on the same page.

00:08:49.039 --> 00:08:52.760
So for this example I have up here, making metadata.

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:56.400
And very loosely, metadata is literally just data about data.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:09:02.479
What helped me help everybody else around me to kind of help me with what they wanted

00:09:02.479 --> 00:09:05.239
was to make sure that they understood what was happening.

00:09:05.239 --> 00:09:07.640
So what was the name of the file?

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:09.919
Like for the data, how often was it collected?

00:09:09.919 --> 00:09:11.400
How was it collected?

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:16.359
Those simple things we don't think about, it really helps to have it documented somewhere.

00:09:16.359 --> 00:09:20.599
Another example I have is something that I'm terming as assess, attempt, repeat.

00:09:20.599 --> 00:09:21.880
We all do this.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:25.719
How many of you have got to a new organization, saw the way that they were doing something

00:09:25.719 --> 00:09:29.000
and was just like, hmm, this ain't right.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:34.440
So you get in, you assess your situation, all right, and you attempt to make a change.

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:39.280
Now if we're lucky, the attempt is successful and it's great.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:43.080
And what usually happens is that we either have people who have been there that's just

00:09:43.080 --> 00:09:46.599
like we're not doing that or something just doesn't work.

00:09:46.599 --> 00:09:50.760
So when I tried to do this, I would try to make the change outside externally, maybe

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:53.320
in a way that we collect data or anything.

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.960
But nine times out of ten, I ended up having to compromise and make up for it internally

00:09:57.960 --> 00:10:00.359
in my systems.

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:05.000
So speaking of internally, there's also some examples of introducing some structure this

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.359
way.

00:10:06.359 --> 00:10:11.080
So the first example I have here is simply named make clean file structures.

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:14.799
And this is so much more than, like, oh, making sure your folder names are clean and

00:10:14.799 --> 00:10:18.280
making sure your data is in a data folder, your scripts are in a script folder.

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:23.119
This also encompasses knowing how to work with our project files.

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:27.559
This encompasses knowing where you are in your working directory, knowing knowledge about

00:10:27.559 --> 00:10:32.719
working directories, because that's the only way that you're going to get a full flow automation

00:10:32.719 --> 00:10:38.280
process with everything stored organized in a good way and seamless, okay?

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:43.080
And like I said, if you need to know more about working directories or our project files

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:48.760
or anything, Jenny Bryan and all of the amazing people have already made resources for it,

00:10:48.760 --> 00:10:51.760
especially with the here package, and that is linked on my repo.

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:55.239
I'm not going to act like I know about that so much.

00:10:55.239 --> 00:10:59.359
The next example I have is something that I'm terming as modularizing your code.

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:03.299
Now in this example, it's being modularized by data and component.

00:11:03.299 --> 00:11:08.979
So this is a snip from an actual large project I had where I had so many data sources, right?

00:11:08.979 --> 00:11:14.940
So it made sense for me to do the work for each data source within one script.

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:16.500
Now that's only one way to do it.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:21.200
You know, it might work for you and it might not, you know?

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:26.619
But another example that you can also do is modularizing your code by function or by process.

00:11:26.619 --> 00:11:32.700
And I usually do this when I don't have too many data sources and I have a more manageable project.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:36.820
Now in this example, I'm showing three scripts in my working directory here.

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:39.659
I have a docking script, which I'll explain that in the next slide.

00:11:39.659 --> 00:11:44.260
I have a processing script, which is just for doing transformations and cleaning.

00:11:44.260 --> 00:11:50.700
And I have a visualization script or a viz script for short, which is literally just making vizes, right?

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:55.460
So what helped me with these projects was having individual scripts that I could call

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:59.580
on when it was time to use it in the pipeline.

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:03.859
So the last example I have here for structuring internal environments is something that I'm calling

00:12:03.859 --> 00:12:06.299
connecting and chaining where it makes sense.

00:12:06.299 --> 00:12:08.179
And honestly, I could have just called it docking scripts.

00:12:08.179 --> 00:12:09.619
I don't know why I talk too much.

00:12:09.619 --> 00:12:13.580
So an example of a docking script is on these next few slides.

00:12:13.580 --> 00:12:17.979
And I want to stress the importance of, like, the content in it is not so much important,

00:12:17.979 --> 00:12:20.940
but just the logic of what is happening is.

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:27.619
Now, in my terms, in my Megan brain, a docking script is one R script that will literally bring

00:12:27.619 --> 00:12:32.260
in your data, do your cleaning, your validation, do everything that it needs to do,

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:36.619
so that when you hit that source button at the top, everything does what it needs to do,

00:12:36.619 --> 00:12:39.739
and your end result is hopefully a deliverable that you're looking for,

00:12:39.739 --> 00:12:43.859
whether it is a shiny app or a clean dataset.

00:12:43.859 --> 00:12:49.260
So just to get into it just a little bit, the docking script starts just like any other R script will start.

00:12:49.260 --> 00:12:51.219
We'll load in our libraries.

00:12:51.219 --> 00:12:55.539
Then the next section we'll go into is something that I call the data process check here.

00:12:55.539 --> 00:12:59.419
Now, this looks maybe, hopefully not complicated, but this is literally just bringing

00:12:59.419 --> 00:13:04.179
in your data and then determining how you want to have some logic values.

00:13:04.179 --> 00:13:08.539
So if you want to do something to check, like, very simply down here, this last line,

00:13:08.539 --> 00:13:14.020
it's just checking a new dataset against an old dataset to see if the value of rows changed.

00:13:14.020 --> 00:13:15.659
And I don't recommend doing that.

00:13:15.659 --> 00:13:18.299
I don't have time to get into why, but don't do it.

00:13:18.299 --> 00:13:23.380
But you'll get a logic value at the end of this section.

00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:26.739
So then the next section I have here is a logic flow for processing.

00:13:26.739 --> 00:13:30.219
So this is just very simple if scripts, if statements.

00:13:30.219 --> 00:13:36.780
So if the data has updated, we will then tell R to source one of our marginalized codes.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:41.059
We will tell R that, okay, if there's new data, go ahead and process that data.

00:13:41.059 --> 00:13:44.859
If there's new data, go ahead and make a visualization for it.

00:13:44.859 --> 00:13:49.659
So that can look very complicated, obviously, depending on what you got going on in your project.

00:13:49.700 --> 00:13:56.979
But after all of that is done, you can embed options in your docking script to render your output.

00:13:56.979 --> 00:14:00.739
So in this case, it's a simple HTML report.

00:14:00.739 --> 00:14:06.140
And an example of a working, hopefully working, version of this is on the repo you can see.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:11.380
So now that I've zoomed by that and realized that, oh, I needed environmental structure,

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:14.140
my data pipeline looks like this in my head.

00:14:14.140 --> 00:14:15.460
I still don't know what this is.

00:14:15.460 --> 00:14:19.340
And I'm really anal, so I hate that the lines are crooked like that.

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:24.539
So what can I do to try to clear up the image of my mental data pipeline?

00:14:24.539 --> 00:14:26.979
Well, we can add data validations.

00:14:26.979 --> 00:14:30.059
And let me tell you guys, I am exposing myself here,

00:14:30.059 --> 00:14:33.659
because you guys know what I learned about data validations.

00:14:33.659 --> 00:14:36.219
I learned that you have to do them.

00:14:36.219 --> 00:14:40.859
Because if you do not check yourself, you will indeed wreck yourself.

00:14:40.859 --> 00:14:43.500
You absolutely will, okay?

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:47.219
I'm going to be honest, I am not the person to stand up here talking about validations.

00:14:47.260 --> 00:14:50.059
I'm still learning myself, okay?

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:54.260
But I can tell you that the most important thing that I learned was to do them.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:15:00.340
Because, man, I could have saved myself so much pain if I had just checked that damn variable, man.

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:02.219
Oh, my God.

00:15:02.219 --> 00:15:09.179
So what I can do is just give you some examples of some types of validations that I did run into.

00:15:09.179 --> 00:15:11.020
Now, I won't go into all of these specifically.

00:15:11.020 --> 00:15:13.219
This is kind of here just for a think piece.

00:15:13.219 --> 00:15:15.859
So if any of you are doing the same, you can reference this and be like,

00:15:15.859 --> 00:15:19.380
hmm, do I have data that fits this as well?

00:15:19.380 --> 00:15:26.099
Now, something that I did actually learn on my own is that validations can exist externally and internally.

00:15:26.099 --> 00:15:33.940
So in my case, or in my opinion, the best scenario has always been that validations are implemented externally,

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:37.179
whether that's at the point of data collection or whatever.

00:15:37.179 --> 00:15:43.739
If it's externally implemented, it might increase the chances of your data being actually, like,

00:15:43.739 --> 00:15:46.619
workable and clean by the time it gets to you internally.

00:15:46.619 --> 00:15:48.299
Hopefully, it's less work.

00:15:48.299 --> 00:15:53.659
But my usual scenario has been that there's no validation done and that I have to do everything,

00:15:53.659 --> 00:15:56.700
and it feels like it's way more work than it needs to be.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:58.380
But that's just me, right?

00:15:58.380 --> 00:16:00.780
So, okay, I realized I have to do validations.

00:16:00.780 --> 00:16:01.820
That's a thing.

00:16:01.820 --> 00:16:06.500
I did them manually in R, and there's nothing wrong with that, but it can be cumbersome.

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:07.859
But there's packages, guys.

00:16:07.859 --> 00:16:09.179
I didn't know this.

00:16:09.179 --> 00:16:12.619
Shout out to Crystal Lewis, because she told me about the point blank package.

00:16:12.619 --> 00:16:13.380
I was late.

00:16:13.380 --> 00:16:15.299
Like, I literally learned about it two days ago.

00:16:15.299 --> 00:16:16.419
I had to change my slides.

00:16:16.419 --> 00:16:22.380
So this is here for both of us to, or for all of us to learn together.

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:25.700
So if you are also in the dark like I was, we can learn together,

00:16:25.700 --> 00:16:27.500
because I don't know about validations.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:29.020
You just got to do them, guys.

00:16:29.020 --> 00:16:35.659
So, okay, now that we have determined that we needed data validation, this is what my pipeline looks like now.

00:16:35.659 --> 00:16:38.580
I see some shapes, but I'm going to be honest with you guys.

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:40.299
I still don't like those lines.

00:16:40.299 --> 00:16:42.580
So what else can I add?

00:16:42.580 --> 00:16:45.099
So our last point is sustainability.

00:16:45.099 --> 00:16:49.859
Okay, so sustainability can mean and look like a lot of different things.

00:16:49.859 --> 00:16:53.659
And I'm going to be honest, guys, because I was a one-person data team,

00:16:53.659 --> 00:16:59.619
I did not have any bandwidth to do any type of real sustainability efforts.

00:16:59.619 --> 00:17:04.579
But what I was able to do was kind of look at the work that I did do, see, okay,

00:17:04.619 --> 00:17:09.099
what is really going to count for sustainability, or what's going to help with this pipeline,

00:17:09.099 --> 00:17:12.060
and what do I wish I could have done?

00:17:12.060 --> 00:17:15.739
So this is just a quick list of things that I brainstormed of, like, man,

00:17:15.739 --> 00:17:18.859
like, if I had the time to do it, I wish I could.

00:17:18.859 --> 00:17:24.180
But the things that I did highlight and saw here are things that I actually eventually did get to do

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:26.540
before I had left that last position.

00:17:26.540 --> 00:17:30.459
And my point of putting this up here, again, is a think piece slide.

00:17:30.500 --> 00:17:37.819
So what I want all of you to take away from this part of the session is to kind of ask yourself,

00:17:37.819 --> 00:17:40.939
do you or your organization, wherever you're working with your data,

00:17:40.939 --> 00:17:43.859
do you guys have sustainability efforts in place,

00:17:43.859 --> 00:17:48.619
or are you in a cyclic cycle of just reaching the next deadline?

00:17:48.619 --> 00:17:51.819
And if so, are there ways to start incorporating,

00:17:51.819 --> 00:17:56.859
making some sustainability efforts to do some QA or QI on your pipelines?

00:17:56.859 --> 00:17:59.579
So the last thing I can share with you guys is just some really,

00:17:59.579 --> 00:18:03.260
really quick examples of things I tried to do to try to document, right?

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:08.099
Because with me being a one-person data team, the best thing I had to do was document everything

00:18:08.099 --> 00:18:13.619
so that people that didn't code or didn't do data could understand what needed to happen,

00:18:13.619 --> 00:18:18.420
especially when I ended up resigning so that, you know, my work didn't just fall apart.

00:18:18.420 --> 00:18:24.660
So this is an example that I have fully on the repo as well, and this is a data workflow map.

00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:28.500
So what helped me was actually visualizing all the different data sources that I had going

00:18:28.500 --> 00:18:31.739
into one of my pipelines, literally explaining where it was coming from,

00:18:31.739 --> 00:18:36.660
but then visualizing what's happening inside of R for other people.

00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:40.140
Another example, I think this looks really similar to a SQL schema.

00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:43.140
I'm sorry, I suck at SQL, so I don't know if that's true.

00:18:43.140 --> 00:18:48.140
But pretty much, again, just a readable version so that people that wasn't working

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:52.459
in data can look and say, okay, we have these data sets, and these are the variables in it,

00:18:52.459 --> 00:18:56.260
and these are the possible ways we can relate them to one another.

00:18:56.260 --> 00:19:01.219
Okay, so now that I've zoomed by all that, let's recap.

00:19:01.219 --> 00:19:07.819
So this was my pipeline in my head before we did anything, when we just jumped in headfirst.

00:19:07.819 --> 00:19:10.900
This is what it looked like when we started to investigate that environment,

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:12.900
ask questions about the data.

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:15.739
This is what it looked like when we added some structure,

00:19:15.739 --> 00:19:21.699
when we realized data validation was a thing, and when we tried to add some sustainability.

00:19:21.699 --> 00:19:22.619
And you know what?

00:19:22.619 --> 00:19:28.339
I still don't know what this is a picture of, but I know that it looks kind of pretty,

00:19:28.339 --> 00:19:32.140
and that it has some clear shapes, some straight lines, and some colors,

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:35.500
and maybe that's the point, right?

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:39.339
So if you are someone that's just starting out in data science or teaching yourself how

00:19:39.339 --> 00:19:44.900
to use R like I was, something that you may have learned is that having things just be

00:19:44.900 --> 00:19:47.579
functional can be just enough.

00:19:47.579 --> 00:19:50.939
And sometimes you may never even know everything about the data you're dealing

00:19:50.939 --> 00:19:55.540
with, but you can appreciate the beauty of the unknowns and the efforts that have been

00:19:55.540 --> 00:19:58.739
made to create the pipeline that you do have to work with.

00:19:58.739 --> 00:20:01.699
Of course, through time, you want to evolve and use best practices and feel

00:20:01.699 --> 00:20:05.819
that we're 100% knowledgeable in what we do, but my hope is that I've given you guys

00:20:05.819 --> 00:20:09.819
something useful to take back with you today, to try to make this process of making

00:20:09.819 --> 00:20:13.939
data pipelines a little less painful, especially if you're going to do the same

00:20:13.939 --> 00:20:17.020
thing that I did and make them from scratch in R.

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:18.020
Thank you for listening, guys.

00:20:18.020 --> 00:20:19.099
Thank you.

